I'm unable to communicate with an mbed-based I2C slave using an LPC1549. Here is the code I'm using to reproduce the problem:

### I2C Master Code (running on LPC1549)
```c++
#include "mbed.h"

I2C i2c(SDA, SCL);
char buff[13];

int main()
{
    i2c.frequency(100000);

    //Write some data to the slave
    sprintf(buff, "Hello World!");
    if (i2c.write(0xAA, buff, sizeof(buff)) != 0) {
        printf("Write error!\n");
    }
    printf("Master sent: \"%s\"\n", buff);

    //Read the data back from the slave
    memset(buff, 0, sizeof(buff));
    if (i2c.read(0xAA, buff, sizeof(buff)) != 0) {
        printf("Read error!\n");
    }
    printf("Master got: \"%s\"\n", buff);

    while (1);
}
```
**Output**
```
Write error!
Master sent: "Hello World!"
Read error!
Master got: ""
```

### I2C Slave Code (running on LPC11U24)
```c++
#include "mbed.h"

I2CSlave i2c(p28, p27);
char buff[13];

int main()
{
    i2c.frequency(100000);
    i2c.address(0xAA);

    while (1) {
        int rxStatus = i2c.receive();
        if (rxStatus == I2CSlave::WriteAddressed) {
            i2c.read(buff, sizeof(buff));
            printf("Slave got: \"%s\"\n", buff);
        } else if (rxStatus == I2CSlave::ReadAddressed) {
            i2c.write(buff, sizeof(buff));
            printf("Slave sent: \"%s\"\n", buff);
        }
    }
}
```
**Output**
```
Slave got: "Hello World!"
```

The I2C master code works fine on an LPC11U68, but throws up errors on an LPC1549. I've traced these errors to _i2c_api.c_ [line 122](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/blob/master/targets/TARGET_NXP/TARGET_LPC15XX/i2c_api.c#L122) and [line 187](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/blob/master/targets/TARGET_NXP/TARGET_LPC15XX/i2c_api.c#L187), but I haven't been able to figure out what's causing them.

### Description
- Type: Enhancement 

----------------------------------------------------------------
## Enhancement

The `callback` function and all its overloads is a generator of `Callback` objects. Its main purpose is to avoid typing of the type of the `Callback` the user wants and avoid too many callbacks objects on the stack: 

```c++
void foo(const Callback<void(int, int)>&);

class Bar { 
public:
  void handler(int, int);
};

static Bar bar;

void qux() { 
  // inject the callback in foo with callback generator.
  // the temporary callback will be destroyed right after the function invocation
  foo(mbed::callback(&bar, &Bar::handler));

  // inject the callback in foo by constructing it manually
  // the callback object will be destroyed at the end of the scope
  { 
    Callback<void(int, int)> bar_handler(&bar, &Bar::handler);
    foo(bar_handler);
  }
}
```

To generate the proper `Callback` type, the `callback` function relies on template type deduction but the type deduction can fail in sometimes for valid use case:

```c++
void foo(const Callback<void(int, int)>&);

class Bar { 
public:
  void handler(int, int);
};

class BarDerived { 
public:
  void qux() { 
     // 1. error no match for callback(BarDerived*, void(Bar::*)(int, int))
     foo(mbed::callback(this, &BarDerived::handler));

     // 2. error void Bar::handler(int, int) protected in this context.
     foo(mbed::callback(this, &Bar::handler));

     // 3. error void Bar::handler(int, int) protected in this context.
     foo(mbed::callback(static_cast<Bar*>(this), &Bar::handler));

     // 4. correct
     foo(mbed::callback(static_cast<Bar*>(this), &BarDerived::handler)); 
  }
};

```

**Suggested enhancement**

* Points `2` and `3` can't be addressed by code but can't be addressed by documentation. Since it is very difficult to track the actual error when the compiler spit hundreds of errors on the command line, it would be interesting to have a list of the common errors users might encounter when they use callback.

* Point `1` can be addressed by relaxing the constraints of the types in input of the callback function, For the example presented earlier, the type of the expected callback has this form:
```c++
template<typename T, typename R, typename A0>
Callback<R(A0)> callback(T *obj, R (T::*func)(A0)) {
    return Callback<R(A0)>(obj, func);
}
```
Since C++ allows derived objects to call parents member functions, it is not safe to assume that the same `T` is applicable for the object and the pointer to the member function. 

One solution would be to add another type in the template parameter list to untie the object type from the pointer to member function type: 

```c++
template<typename T, typename U, typename R, typename A0>
Callback<R(A0)> callback(T *obj, R (U::*func)(A0)) {
    return Callback<R(A0)>(obj, func);
}
```

Of course the change should be reflected in the `Callback` class to make it work. Any type error should be catch at a latter point (where `(obj->*func)(...)` is instantiated). This change doesn't endanger the type safety of the callback class.

